Besides the obvious variables of title, genre, director, year, and duration, the rest of the variables are as follows:

  • gross : The gross earnings in the US box office, not adjusted for inflation
  • budget: The movie's budget
  • cast_facebook_likes: the number of facebook likes cast memebrs received
  • votes: the number of people who voted for (or rated) the movie in IMDB
  • reviews: the number of reviews for that movie
  • rating: IMDB average rating

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

movies = movies.assign(return_on_budget=lambda x: x["gross"] / x["budget"])

table5 = (
    movies
    .loc[:, ["title", "return_on_budget", "rating"]]
    .sort_values("return_on_budget", ascending=False)
)
print(table5)

correlation = table5["return_on_budget"].corr(table5["rating"])
print("Correlation between ROI and Rating:", correlation)

movies["log_roi"] = np.log1p(movies["return_on_budget"])

sns.scatterplot(data=movies, x="log_roi", y="rating", alpha=0.6)
sns.regplot(data=movies, x="log_roi", y="rating", scatter=False, color="red")
plt.title("Do Higher ROI Movies Get Better Ratings? (Log ROI)")
plt.xlabel("Log(1 + ROI)")
plt.ylabel("Rating")
plt.ylim(0, 10)
plt.show()

#Since most of the ratings are between 5 to 8, I apply log on them to check "If the high rating means high ROI". 
#The plot shows us that for those movies having high ROI, they are not necessarily high ratings, but not likely to be super-low ratings.

print(
    "Since most ratings fall between 5 and 8, I applied a log transformation to ROI "
    "to better check whether high ratings are associated with high ROI.\n"
)
print(
    "The plot suggests that movies with high ROI are not necessarily highly rated, "
    "but they are also less likely to have extremely low ratings."
)

plt.ylabel("Gross (Box Office)")

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.scatterplot(data=movies, x="cast_facebook_likes", y="gross", alpha=0.6)
plt.xscale("log")
plt.yscale("log")
plt.title("Gross vs Cast Facebook Likes (Log Scales)")
plt.xlabel("Cast Facebook Likes (log)")
plt.ylabel("Gross (log)")

I map cast_facebook_likes to the X-axis and gross to the Y-axis;

suggesting that cast popularity is not a strong predictor of box office gross.
""")

plt.title("Gross vs Budget")
plt.xlabel("Budget")
plt.ylabel("Gross (Box Office)")
plt.show()

print("""The scatterplot suggests a positive but noisy relationship between budget and gross: 
higher-budget films tend to earn more at the box office, 
though budget alone is not a perfect predictor of success.""")

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


g = sns.relplot(
    data=movies, 
    x="rating", 
    y="gross", 
    col="genre",       
    col_wrap=5,        
    kind="scatter", 
    height=4, 
    alpha=0.6
)

g.set_titles("{col_name}")          
g.set_xlabels("IMDB Rating")        
g.set_ylabels("Gross (Box Office)") 
plt.suptitle("Gross vs Rating by Genre", y=1.02)  
plt.show()

print("""The faceted scatterplots show that IMDB ratings are not a strong predictor of box office gross:
many high-rated films earned little while some lower-rated blockbusters earned massive grosses
and the dataset also looks strange because of extreme outliers, skewed distributions, and genres with very sparse data.""")

The faceted scatterplots show that IMDB ratings are not a strong predictor of box office gross:
many high-rated films earned little while some lower-rated blockbusters earned massive grosses
and the dataset also looks strange because of extreme outliers, skewed distributions, and genres with very sparse data.

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.ticker import FuncFormatter

df = movies.copy()

for col in ["budget", "gross", "rating", "cast_facebook_likes", "title"]:
    if col != "title":
        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors="coerce")

df = df.dropna(subset=["budget","gross","rating","cast_facebook_likes","title"])
df = df[(df["budget"] > 0) & (df["gross"] > 0)]

df["rating_band"] = pd.cut(
    df["rating"],
    bins=[0, 6, 7, 8, 10],
    labels=["≤6", "6–7", "7–8", "≥8"],
    include_lowest=True
)
likes = df["cast_facebook_likes"].fillna(0).clip(0, df["cast_facebook_likes"].quantile(0.99))
sizes = 50 + 450 * (likes / likes.max()) 


sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))

ax = sns.scatterplot(
    data=df,
    x="budget", y="gross",
    hue="rating_band", size=sizes, sizes=(50,500),
    alpha=0.65, linewidth=0.2, edgecolor="black", palette="viridis"
)
